{{Taxobox | name = ''Bacteriophage T5'' | image = | image_caption = | virus_group = i | ordo = ''[[Caudovirales]]'' | familia = ''[[Siphoviridae]]'' | genus = | species = ''Bacteriophage T5'' }}
'''Bacteriophage T5''' is a caudal [[virus]] within the family ''[[Siphoviridae]]''. This [[bacteriophage]] specifically infects ''[[Escherichia coli|E. coli]]'' bacterial cells and follows a [[Lytic cycle|lytic life cycle]].
== Structure and genome == The T5 structure includes a 90 nanometer icosahedral [[capsid]] and a 250 nanometer-long flexible, non-contractile tail. The capsid contains the phage's 121750 base pair, double-stranded DNA genome.<ref>Effantin G. et al. Bacteriophage T5 structure reveals similarities with HK97 and T4 suggesting evolutionary relationships. J Mol Biol. (2006) 361, 993–1002</ref>
== Infection == Bacteriophage T5 has been shown to infect ''E. coli'' after its receptor binding protein, pb5, binds to the host cell's outer membrane [[ferrichrome]] transporter, FhuA. The binding triggers structural changes in pb5 and eventually leads to DNA release from the phage capsid.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Flayhan|first=A|author2=Wien, F|author3= Paternostre, M|author4= Boulanger, P|author5= Breyton, C|title=New insights into pb5, the receptor binding protein of bacteriophage T5, and its interaction with its Escherichia coli receptor FhuA.|journal=Biochimie|date=Sep 2012|volume=94|issue=9|pages=1982–9|pmid=22659573|doi=10.1016/j.biochi.2012.05.021}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Basit|first=H|author2=Shivaji Sharma, K|author3=Van der Heyden, A|author4=Gondran, C|author5=Breyton, C|author6=Dumy, P|author7=Winnik, FM|author8= Labbé, P|title=Amphipol mediated surface immobilization of FhuA: a platform for label-free detection of the bacteriophage protein pb5.|journal=Chemical communications (Cambridge, England)|date=May 11, 2012|pmid=22576748|doi=10.1039/c2cc31107k|volume=48|pages=6037}}</ref>
