{{For|crater on the Moon|Huggins (lunar crater)}} {{Infobox Mars crater | name = Huggins Crater | image = HugginsMartianCrater.jpg | caption = Topographic location of Huggins Crater. The map is partly oval due to the mapping marked at the equator which makes features north or south of it oval | region = [[Eridania quadrangle]] | coordinates = {{coord|49.4|S|150.6|E|globe:mars_type:landmark|display=inline,title}} | discoverer = | diameter = 90 km | eponym = [[William Huggins]] }} '''Huggins''' is an [[impact crater]] in the [[Eridania quadrangle]] of [[Mars]], located at 49.4°S latitude and 204.4°W longitude, and is part of [[Terra Cimmeria]]. It is 90.0&nbsp;km in diameter and was named after [[William Huggins]], and the name was approved in 1973 by the International Astronomical Union (IAU) [[Working Group for Planetary System Nomenclature]] (WGPSN).<ref>{{cite web|title=Gazetteer of Planetary Nomenclature {{!}} Huggins|url=http://planetarynames.wr.usgs.gov/Feature/2575|website=usgs.gov|publisher=[[International Astronomical Union]]|accessdate=4 March 2015}}</ref> [[File:Wikihuggins.jpg|thumb|left|Huggins Crater, as seen by CTX camera (on [[Mars Reconnaissance Orbiter]]).]][[File:Wikihugginsdunesdevils.jpg|thumb|left|Dunes and [[dust devil tracks]] on floor of Huggins Crater, as seen by CTX camera (on Mars Reconnaissance Orbiter). Dark streaks on dunes are dust devil tracks. Note: this is an enlargement of the previous image of Huggins Crater.]] Nearby named craters include [[Cruls (crater)|Cruls]] to the northeast, [[Rossby (crater)|Rossby]] almost to the east, [[Campbell (Martian crater)|Campbell]] to the southeast, and the small [[Tycho Brahe (Martian crater)|Tycho Brahe]] to the west and the larger [[Kepler (Martian crater)|Kepler]]. West of Huggins is a feature known as [[Eridania Scopulus]].
