{{Infobox astronaut | name =Tamara Elizabeth "Tammy" Jernigan | image =Tamara E. Jernigan.jpg | type =[[NASA]] Astronaut | status =Retired | nationality =American | birth_date ={{Birth date and age|1959|05|07}} | birth_place =[[Chattanooga, Tennessee]] | occupation =[[Scientist]] | selection =[[List of astronauts by selection#1985|1985 NASA Group]] | time =63d 01h 24m | eva1 =1 | eva2 = 7 hours 55 minutes | mission =[[STS-40]], [[STS-52]], [[STS-67]], [[STS-80]], [[STS-96]] | insignia =[[Image:Sts-40-patch.png|30px]][[Image:Sts-52-patch.png|30px]][[Image:Sts-67-patch.svg|30px]][[Image:Sts-80-patch.png|30px]][[Image:Sts-96-patch.png|30px]] |}} '''Tamara Elizabeth "Tammy" Jernigan, Ph.D.''' (born May 7, 1959, in [[Chattanooga, Tennessee]]) is an American scientist and former [[NASA]] [[astronaut]] and a veteran of five shuttle missions.
==Education== Jernigan attended [[Santa Fe High School (California)|Santa Fe High School]] in [[Santa Fe Springs, CA]]. She graduated in 1977. Jernigan attended [[Stanford University]], where she earned a B.S. degree in physics in 1981, an M.S. in engineering science in 1983. At the [[University of California, Berkeley]], she received an M.S. in astronomy in 1985. In 1988 she was awarded a Ph.D. in space physics and astronomy from [[Rice University]].
==NASA career== [[File:Tamara Jernigan stamp.jpg|left|thumb|150px|Jernigan on 1995 [[Azerbaijan|Azeri]] postage stamp.]] [[File:Tamara E. Jernigan Discovery crew.jpg|left|thumb|250px|Tamara Jernigan performing EVA during [[STS-96]]]] She entered the [[NASA]] Astronaut Corps in 1986 and retired in 2001. Her first trip to space was on June 5, 1991.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/781937044|title=Space sciences|date=2012|publisher=Gale, Cengage Learning|others=Gale (Firm)|isbn=9780028662190|edition=2nd|location=Detroit, Mich.|oclc=781937044}}</ref> She flew on five [[Space Shuttle program]] missions (three on ''[[Space Shuttle Columbia|Columbia]]'' and one each on ''[[Space Shuttle Endeavour|Endeavour]]'' and ''[[Space Shuttle Discovery|Discovery]]'') and logged 1512 hours in space. In her last mission on ''Discovery'' in 1999, she performed an [[extra-vehicular activity]] for 7 hours and 55 minutes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jsc.nasa.gov/Bios/htmlbios/jernigan.html|title=Astronaut Bio: T. Jernigan 11/2001|website=www.jsc.nasa.gov}}</ref>
==Personal== She currently resides in Pleasanton, CA. She is married and has a child, Jeffrey Wisoff with former astronaut [[Peter Wisoff]].
