'''Valeri Leonidovich Barsukov''' (Валерий Леонидович Барсуков) (March 14, 1928 – July 22, 1992) was a [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] [[geologist]].<ref>{{Cite book|title = Soviet Robots in the Solar System: Mission Technologies and Discoveries|last = Huntress, Jr.|first = Wesley T.|publisher = Spring Science + Business Media|year = 2011|isbn = 9781441978981|location = New York|pages = 19|last2 = Marov|first2 = Mikhail Ya.|url = https://books.google.com/books?id=rgl_C0XrKTUC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref> He worked in comparative [[planetology]] and the geochemistry of space. He was director of the [[V. I. Vernadsky Institute of Geochemistry]] from 1976 to 1992. In 1987 he received the [[Vladimir I. Vernadsky|V.I. Vernadsky]] Gold Medal for his work. A [[Impact crater|crater]] on [[Mars]] was named after him.<ref>
