'''WISEP J190648.47+401106.8''' (shortened to '''W1906+40''') is a [[Brown dwarf#Spectral class L|L-dwarf star]]. In 2015 it was shown to have on its surface a storm the size of [[Jupiter]]'s [[Great Red Spot]]. The storm rotates around the star roughly every 9 hours and has lasted since at least 2013, when observations of the storm began.<ref>{{cite web |title=NASA Telescopes Detect Jupiter-Like Storm on Small Star |url=http://www.jpl.nasa.gov/news/news.php?feature=4786 |work=[[Jet Propulsion Laboratory]] |date=10 December 2015 |accessdate=11 December 2015}}</ref>

The star is 53 light-years from Earth, has an intrinsic brightness of 0.0002 that of the sun, a radius of 0.9 Jupiters, and a surface temperature of 2,311 K. The star emits significant flares.<ref name="Simbad">{{cite web |title=WISEP J190648.47+401106.8 |url=http://simbad.u-strasbg.fr/simbad/sim-id?Ident=WISEP+J190648.47%2B401106.8 |work=SIMBAD |date=26 November 2015 |accessdate=11 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Mike |last=Wall |title=Dwarf Star Blasts out Stunningly Powerful Flares |url=http://www.space.com/21412-dwarf-star-flares-kepler-mission.html |work=[[Space.com]] |date=3 June 2013 |accessdate=11 December 2015}}</ref><ref name="Gizis-et-al">{{cite journal |first=John E. |last=Gizis |display-authors=etal |title=Kepler Monitoring of an L Dwarf II. Clouds with Multiyear Lifetimes |arxiv=1509.07186|date=24 September 2015 |doi=10.1088/0004-637X/813/2/104 |volume=813 |journal=The Astrophysical Journal |page=104 |bibcode=2015ApJ...813..104G}}</ref>

Distance 53.3 (+1.17, -1.11) light years.<ref name="Gizis-et-al" />

